  🔠 call_01_NiIsfu6DfB3XyCbDHemv4222 | Return {'query': {'original': 'Redis Streams exactly-once delivery consumer groups architecture', 'show_strict_warning': False, 'is_navigational': False, 'is_news_breaking': False, 'spellcheck_off': False, 'country': 'us', 'bad_results': False, 'should_fallback': False, 'postal_code': '', 'city': '', 'header_country': '', 'more_results_available': True, 'state': ''}, 'results': [{'title': 'Node.js + Redis Streams: Exactly-Once Event Pipelines with Consumer Groups | by Yamishift | Medium', 'url': 'https://medium.com/@komalbaparmar007/node-js-redis-streams-exactly-once-event-pipelines-with-consumer-groups-33318dfbd591', 'snippet': 'Learn Node.js + Redis Streams consumer groups for “exactly-once” pipelines: <strong>XREADGROUP, PEL recovery, XAUTOCLAIM, idempotency, and DLQs</strong>.', 'source': 'brave'}, {'title': 'How to Implement Redis Streams Consumer Groups', 'url': 'https://oneuptime.com/blog/post/2026-01-30-redis-streams-consumer-groups/view', 'snippet': 'When you create a consumer group, <strong>Redis tracks which messages have been delivered and acknowledged</strong>. This tracking happens at the group level, so different groups can process the same stream independently. flowchart TB subgraph Stream[&quot;Redis ...', 'source': 'brave'}, {'title': 'Redis Streams | Docs', 'url': 'https://redis.io/docs/latest/develop/data-types/streams/', 'snippet': 'Starting with Redis 8.2, the XACKDEL, XDELEX, XADD, and XTRIM commands provide fine-grained control over how stream operations interact with multiple consumer groups, simplifying the coordination of message processing across different applications. Beginning with Redis 8.6, Redis streams support idempotent message processing (at-most-once production) to prevent duplicate entries when using at-least-once delivery patterns.', 'source': 'brave'}, {'title': 'How to Build Event-Driven Architecture with Redis Streams', 'url': 'https://oneuptime.com/blog/post/2026-03-31-redis-event-driven-architecture-streams/view', 'snippet': 'MAX_DELIVERY_COUNT = 3 DLQ_STREAM = &quot;events:dlq&quot; def process_pending_events(stream: str, group: str, consumer: str): pending = r.xpending_range(stream, group, min=&quot;-&quot;, max=&quot;+&quot;, count=100) for entry in pending: if entry[&quot;times_delivered&quot;] &gt;= MAX_DELIVERY_COUNT: # Move to DLQ raw = r.xrange(stream, entry[&quot;message_id&quot;], entry[&quot;message_id&quot;], count=1) if raw: _, event = raw[0] event[&quot;original_stream&quot;] = stream event[&quot;delivery_count&quot;] = str(entry[&quot;times_delivered&quot;]) r.xadd(DLQ_STREAM, event) r.xack(stream, group, entry[&quot;message_id&quot;]) print(f&quot;Moved {entry[&#x27;message_id&#x27;]} to DLQ&quot;) Redis Streams provides the building blocks of a reliable event-driven architecture: persistent event storage, consumer group fanout, acknowledgment-based at-least-once delivery, and pending entry tracking for retries.', 'source': 'brave'}, {'title': 'Microservices Interservice Communication with Redis Streams', 'url': 'https://redis.io/tutorials/howtos/solutions/microservices/interservice-communication/', 'snippet': 'Redis Streams sits in a sweet spot for many microservices architectures: it <strong>provides message persistence, consumer groups, and replay capability with the operational simplicity of Redis</strong>.', 'source': 'brave'}, {'title': 'How to Build a Distributed Event Bus with Redis Streams', 'url': 'https://oneuptime.com/blog/post/2026-03-31-redis-distributed-event-bus/view', 'snippet': 'import redis import json import ... &quot;ORD-9901&quot;, &quot;user_id&quot;: 42, &quot;total&quot;: 149.99, }) <strong>Each subscribing service creates its own consumer group so it gets every event independently</strong>:...', 'source': 'brave'}, {'title': 'How to Scale Event Consumers with Redis Consumer Groups', 'url': 'https://oneuptime.com/blog/post/2026-01-21-redis-consumer-groups-scaling/view', 'snippet': 'Exactly-once semantics: <strong>Each message is delivered to only one consumer</strong> · flowchart TB RS[Redis Stream] --&gt; CG[Consumer Group: processors] CG --&gt; C1[Consumer-1] CG --&gt; C2[Consumer-2] CG --&gt; C3[Consumer-3]', 'source': 'brave'}, {'title': 'Manage streams and consumer groups in Redis Insight | Docs', 'url': 'https://redis.io/docs/latest/develop/tools/insight/insight-stream-consumer/', 'snippet': 'You get a message whether the ... data flow. One way you can scale consumers is consumer groups, which <strong>allows multiple instances of the same consumer or same code to work as a team to process the stream</strong>....', 'source': 'brave'}, {'title': 'Redis Streams Decoded: 15 Questions That Changed How I Think About Message Queues | by Pur4v | Medium', 'url': 'https://medium.com/@pur4v/redis-streams-decoded-15-questions-that-changed-how-i-think-about-message-queues-24bd0dbe3189', 'snippet': 'Stream + 1 consumer group + 10 consumers: - Stream data: ~104MB (same as above) - Group metadata: - last_delivered_id: 16 bytes - entries_read counter: 8 bytes - PEL (pending entries): - If 1000 pending: ~1000 × 64 bytes = 64KB - Consumer metadata: - 10 consumers × 256 bytes = 2.56KB - Total overhead: ~67KB (0.06%) // What Redis stores for each pending message struct streamNACK { mstime_t delivery_time; // 8 bytes uint64_t delivery_count; // 8 bytes streamConsumer *consumer; // 8 bytes (pointer) // + some rax tree overhead // Total: ~64 bytes per pending message }', 'source': 'brave'}, {'title': 'How to Use Redis Streams for Event Sourcing', 'url': 'https://oneuptime.com/blog/post/2026-01-21-redis-streams-event-sourcing/view', 'snippet': 'Consumer groups enable distributed message processing with delivery tracking. # Create group starting from beginning XGROUP CREATE events mygroup 0 # Create group starting from end (new messages only) XGROUP CREATE events mygroup $ # Create with MKSTREAM (create stream if not exists) XGROUP CREATE events mygroup 0 MKSTREAM # Create from specific ID XGROUP CREATE events mygroup 1609459200000-0 · # Read new messages for consumer XREADGROUP GROUP mygroup consumer1 COUNT 10 STREAMS events &gt; # Read pending messages (re-read unacknowledged) XREADGROUP GROUP mygroup consumer1 COUNT 10 STREAMS events 0 # Blocking read XREADGROUP GROUP mygroup consumer1 BLOCK 5000 COUNT 10 STREAMS events &gt;', 'source': 'brave'}], 'total': 10, 'page': 1, 'error': None}
