  🔠 call_00_CsKJpiaWHqpttctqd3Yg3345 | Return {'content': '## Summary\n\nThis blog post by Nawaz Dhandala (March 31, 2026) provides a technical side-by-side comparison of Redis Streams and Apache Kafka as event-streaming solutions, covering core concepts (consumer groups, ordering, retention, throughput), code examples for basic operations, and guidance on when to use each technology.\n\n## Key Points\n\n1. **Redis Streams** use XADD/XREAD/XGROUP commands, are in-memory (with optional AOF persistence), offer total ordering within a single stream, and are bounded by memory (MAXLEN). Throughput is ~100K messages/sec per stream. (Source: "Side-by-Side Comparison" table)\n2. **Kafka** uses producers/topics/partitions, persists to disk (log segments), provides per-partition ordering, and scales to millions of messages/sec across partitions. It supports exactly-once semantics via idempotent producers and transactions. (Source: "Side-by-Side Comparison" table)\n3. Redis Streams handle backpressure via `MAXLEN ~` to cap stream size; Kafka uses configurable retention (time- or size-based) such as `retention.ms` and `retention.bytes`. (Source: "Handling Backpressure" section)\n4. Dead-letter handling in Redis is manual—move failed messages to a separate stream using `XADD` and `XACK`; Kafka can use `errors.deadletterqueue.topic.name` via Connect or custom consumer logic. (Source: "Dead Letter Handling" section)\n5. Choose Redis Streams when already using Redis, message volume fits in memory, and simplicity matters; choose Kafka for infinite retention, >1M msg/sec throughput, exactly-once delivery, and multi-consumer independence. (Source: "When to Choose..." sections)\n\n## Technical Details\n\n**Redis Streams Command Examples** (Source: "Redis Streams Basics")\n- `XADD orders * user_id 42 item_id 100 qty 2` – append with auto-generated ID\n- `XREADGROUP GROUP fulfillment worker1 COUNT 10 BLOCK 5000 STREAMS orders >` – consume in group\n- `XACK orders fulfillment 1700000000000-0` – acknowledge message\n- `XPENDING orders fulfillment - + 10` – list pending unacked messages\n- `XADD orders MAXLEN ~ 10000 * user_id 42 item_id 100` – capped stream (approx max 10,000 entries)\n\n**Kafka Configuration Examples** (Source: "Kafka Basics")\n- Producer: set `bootstrap.servers`, serializers, `producer.send(new ProducerRecord<>("orders", key, value))`\n- Consumer: set `group.id`, disable auto-commit, `consumer.subscribe(...)`, `consumer.poll()`, `consumer.commitSync()`\n- Retention config: `kafka-configs.sh` with `retention.ms=604800000` (7 days) and `retention.bytes=10737418240` (10 GB)\n\n**Comparison Table Highlights** (Source: "Side-by-Side Comparison")\n| Dimension | Redis Streams | Kafka |\n|-----------|---------------|-------|\n| Persistence | In-memory (AOF optional) | Disk (log segments) |\n| Retention | Bounded by MAXLEN or memory | Time/size based (configurable) |\n| Partitioning | Single stream key | Multiple partitions per topic |\n| Ordering | Total order within stream | Per-partition |\n| Throughput | ~100K msg/sec per stream | Millions/sec across partitions |\n| Exactly-once | No | Yes (idempotent producer + transactions) |\n| Ops complexity | Low | High (ZooKeeper/KRaft + Kafka) |\n\n**Dead Letter Python Example for Redis** (Source: "Dead Letter Handling")\n- Moves failed message to `dlq_stream` with error info, then acknowledges original.\n\n## References & Citations\n\n- Blog post: [Redis Streams vs Kafka: A Detailed Comparison](https://oneuptime.com/blog/post/2026-03-31-redis-streams-vs-kafka-detailed-comparison/view)\n- Author: Nawaz Dhandala (@nawazdhandala), Mar 31, 2026\n- Sections: "Redis Streams Basics", "Kafka Basics", "Side-by-Side Comparison", "Handling Backpressure", "Dead Letter Handling", "When to Choose Redis Streams", "When to Choose Kafka"', 'links_on_page': ['https://oneuptime.com/', 'https://oneuptime.com/product/monitoring', 'https://oneuptime.com/product/status-page', 'https://oneuptime.com/product/incident-ma