Saved as `ADR-001-notification-architecture.md`. Here's the summary of the decision:

**Recommendation: Redis Streams** — a definitive choice grounded in the team's specific constraints.

The ADR uses the FEBC framework to evaluate each dimension:

| Dimension | Why Redis Streams wins |
|---|---|
| **Existing infra** | Redis is already deployed; Kafka means a second distributed system to manage |
| **Team capability** | Zero Kafka experience vs. existing Redis knowledge; Streams is learnable in an afternoon |
| **Delivery timeline** | Days for Redis Streams; 3–6 weeks for a production Kafka deployment |
| **Cost** | ~$0 incremental (existing Redis) vs. $600–900/mo for a 3-node Kafka cluster |
| **Throughput** | ~100K msg/sec ceiling vs. our 500 req/s peak (even at 10×) |
| **Ordering** | Per-stream total ordering is sufficient; per-partition Kafka ordering is overkill |
| **Exactly-once** | Redis lacks it natively, but application-level idempotency keys solve it for the 0.1% of traffic that needs it |
| **Operational complexity** | Redis has one config file and no cluster orchestration; Kafka demands broker tuning, ISR monitoring, rebalance management |

The ADR also addresses the real gap: Redis consumer groups lose strict ordering across consumers (round-robin distribution), but at our scale a single consumer per notification type is sufficient, with parallel consumers reserved for non-order-sensitive workloads.
